segments.text: If you record at maximum, or you record at minimum, I believe we're ready to go.
What I usually start off with is a little biographical statement.
What's my name?
Well, I already gave him your name and everything on the beginning of that beforehand.
But you already gave your biographical statement to Billy Halford in the other interview.
So unless there's anything you'd like to add in terms of change.
Changes since then?
Not really.
Same old thing.
And you also talked about how you came to tease, but I would like you to redo that one for us this time.
Oh, I see.
I was at General Dynamics, yeah, when I came here.
I guess Charlie Rodenberger invited me to come make a speech.
I don't know.
I did that.
But in talking to Fred Benson, I complained about the fact that there wasn't a space program at A&M.
And like Fred Benson does, he says, well, won't you come fix that?
So that's how I came here and started the space program.
There was one grant that they had.
One grant, yeah.
John Calhoun had gotten a grant, the first NASA grant in the state of Texas.
And I guess that grant ran until about two years ago.
Was it continuous grant?
It was almost 20 years.
He got it in 62, and I came here in 63, but they hadn't even done anything with it.
They just had it.
So you came specifically to head the Space Technology Division, and it was created when you came?
Right.
What type of space research was done during the 60s?
I've got that, yeah.
Have you seen this?
I've got a copy of it.
Okay, that will give you... We tried to broaden it out into the whole university, and to some extent we did, but it still was, I'd say, three-quarters engineering.
Really, Rice took over the space science part of it.
And our program was primarily engineering, although there were some over in the science college.
Of course, our wind tunnel was used by NASA throughout and still is.
Was it used during the 60s?
When did you revamp it?
Yeah, it was in the late 60s that they started using the wind tunnel.
work on reentry projects.
But it got heavily used when they started the space shuttle design.
But I knew it had been there, and you'd said that when you came it was filled with hay.
When was it that it was cleared out?
Oh, it was cleared.
We got the hay out of it in a couple of years.
But I wasn't sure if it had just laid dormant until the shuttle program, or if it had been in use.
No, it had been in use before that.
Dr. Strickland, who died, was in our space, heavily sponsored by NASA, mainly in structures research and nose cone re-entry research.
There have been few changes in T's administration since you've been here.
Yes.
I guess for
Let's see, I got here in 63, and I was made associate director by Benson and Ludeke when Ludeke was there.
See, he was associate director, and then was made acting president.
And I can't remember exactly when that was.
But it probably was late 60s or 70s.
So I've been associate director for probably 15 years.
70 is when you became associate assistant in 63.
Okay, and associate in 70.
Yeah, that makes sense.
Were you here when Cahan was still here?
Cahan, he was with the Research Foundation.
Oh, Cahan.
Cahan, okay.
Cahan.
No, I wasn't.
He left when I got here.
Did you notice any major change in the direction T's took in research when Rudder died?
No.
I have seen no major change in T's type or thrust of research since I've been here, and I still don't see any.
What do you see as the major thrust?
It's applied research.
CTs is a separate state agency, and its real role as far as its creators, and that's the state legislature, is industrial development, not higher education.
So most of our research has been applied.
It has been heavily associated with Texas industry and national industry to some extent.
But not like Harvard or Yale.
We're very proud of doing applied research.
We do basic, but I don't ever remember any strong thrust to do basic research.
Nor do I see any now.
With the changes in upper administration that you've
the changes between reporting to the chancellor and the president.
Has that changed your roles?
My role?
No.
Definitely.
I've been very fortunate.
Benson is an absolutely gorgeous boss.
He lets you do your job.
And I don't see why it's important.
They're both pretty much alike.
And I have run the program.
And they've done the politicking, which is the way I want it.
So by running the program, what do you mean?
All of the division had to report for me.
Has that been that way since you became an associate?
Always has been that way.
Was it that way in the 60s, too, when you were assistant?
No, not when I was assistant.
That occurred.
See, at one time...
TTI reported to me also.
But see, I sit in the line.
And that's the way I'm going to play.
Who do you deal with outside the system?
Outside the A&M system?
Well, I have up until six or seven years ago.
dealt with Washington a great deal, and all the sponsors, NSF, and the Department of Defense.
See, I was in the Army 20 years.
It's incredible.
In the last six years, I haven't done that.
Dr. Bain has done most of that.
So in the recent past, I have strictly run the Engineering Experiment Station.
And done very little dealing outside the system.
I know in the 60s.
In the early days, of course, I was the leg man to get the Tate Building built.
So I spent a couple of years in Washington almost.
Whose idea was the Tate Building?
Winardi.
His original idea didn't happen.
He wanted it to be an activation analysis building.
That was his main interest.
That was his claim to fame.
But that wasn't broad enough to sell a building in Nassau.
So really, this report was a dedication to the building.
But who got the building?
Then you doubt about that.
Only Teague got the building.
All I did was make it reasonable for Nassau to give it to us.
But had it not been for Teague, it wouldn't be there.
I think everybody would say.
But they had a reasonable reason to give it to us.
According to letters written back and forth to the president at that time, in 1963 when they appointed you assistant director, you were supposed to be the wonder child of grant money.
There's no such thing as the wonder child of grant money.
Do you know how you get grant money?
How do you get it?
Very, very simple.
You find a man who can do the job that somebody wants done and has some money.
And then you arrange to get them face-to-face, the two people who technically know the details of what's going on.
Now, to get them face-to-face takes some doing, and I'm rather good at that.
But nobody can get somebody else a grant, unless it's politics, and you can't live on politics.
What gets you a grant is to...
He's technically competent to do a job a man wants done who's got some money to pay for.
It's that simple.
But you've got to get the two together.
You've got to get them together.
Is that what TEAS does, in your opinion?
Yeah, that's what TEAS does.
TEAS knows the talent throughout engineering, and it knows the problems throughout the country.
And you hear, well...
Right now, for example, the Air Force very much wants to apply artificial intelligence to manufacturing.
We know that because Dick Thomas is on a committee of the Air Force that's working on that.
And then we know that Don Phillips in industrial is an expert in that.
And then the two get like they did two weeks ago.
And man, it happens.
It's almost a cinch.
It is difficult.
Well, you've got to know it.
If you weren't...
If you've got talented people, getting grants is no problem.
We don't have a money problem.
We have a people problem.
We need more people.
Need more people in the university willing to do research?
Well, see, engineering has been growing so fast.
So you have a combination of problems.
One, the teaching loads are unbelievable, which makes it difficult to talk some guy into doing research when he's teaching more than he should anyway.
And you can't do that for too long.
And I think that's coming around.
But for the last couple of years, it's been pretty bad.
But it's recognized, and once it is, and the people who can fix it know it's a problem, it gets fixed.
But it takes a long time.
Did you have the same problem with teaching loads in the 60s?
They were pretty good about giving you release time?
Yeah.
See, the difference, really, in engineering, if you are doing research, you go off of this budget.
the teaching budget, and you go on to the research budget.
So if there's any cheating going on, it becomes real obvious.
And this arrangement, once you, you're always gonna have these problems in a growth pattern because there's an inertia in what the legislature does and what we can do.
But once you recognize the problem, it can be fixed because we have the organization to do it.
Some people don't.
We do.
Did you notice, not here at T's because you weren't here by then, in the late 50s with Sputnik and you were in the Department of Defense, did that really make a difference?
Sputnik was way before the late 50s.
I was at White Sands Proving Ground when Sputnik went up.
Are those 57?
Okay.
I'm sorry, but you're right.
But I wasn't here.
I was at White Sands.
Yeah, right.
But did you notice there that money started being freed up for research?
Yeah, it did.
Have there been any other...
events like that that you remember since you've been here that have caused money for particular types of research?
It definitely has occurred during the Reagan administration, particularly for basic research.
See, the kind of research engineers do is not nearly as hard to find money for as the kind of research the science college does.
It's just human nature.
They can see an end product in what we're doing.
And they're willing to put the money up if they need the end product.
But since Regan took office, and you can read this almost any place, particularly writings by the head of the National Science Foundation, he certainly has a somewhat bias, but
I do know money for basic research has increased about 50% in the last two or three years.
And we're just beginning to feel that.
And we do need to do more basic research, but people haven't been willing to pay for it.
I do see a trend that they may be willing to pay for it.
But what we do, somebody's got to pay for it.
What was the, I don't know if you know, but the purpose of... And I'll tell you why Reagan's doing that.
He knows this country's in deep trouble economically.
The Japanese are skinning us.
The Germans are skinning us.
And the reason he's doing it is that he feels that will improve our economic posture.
And he's right.
It will.
It'll take a while to do it.
You've got to have the knowledge.
And you'll also notice the National Science Foundation right now is putting way more emphasis on engineering research than they have in the past.
They plan to quadruple the money spent on engineering in the next three years for the same reason, economics.
So there's more money for basic science research, but...
Both in engineering and the sciences.
And engineering is being emphasized all over the place because this is where you're going to improve the economics.
We've forgotten how to build things cheap that work.
You haven't seen any of the cyclical moves before while you were here?
There was a very definite downtrend in the overall research budget.
up until about three years ago.
I guess you'd say from 70 to 79.
Before that, 60 to 70, there was money everywhere, and they didn't know what to do with it.
They're cyclic, yeah.
It was a general slow downturn.
It wasn't any major crash of no funds available.
I'm hoping that right now there's some sense being put into it.
but also a definite increase in funds available.
There's no question but what Texas does not get its fair share.
Of national money?
That's right.
They do not.
For example, there's not a national laboratory in the state.
There's three in New Mexico.
National laboratory?
Los Alamos.
Oh, okay.
That's right.
You already...
I think you already stated your view on the role of TEAS in education, but I'd like to know.
My view on what?
TEAS role in education?
TEAS basic role, as far as the legislature is concerned, who, by the way, has the money that we get from the state.
And that is only about 20% of our budget.
Their opinion of what TEAS is supposed to do is,
to improve the economic stature of the state of Texas.
And if somebody out there goes and tells them, yeah, that's what they're doing, we've got no problems.
But if somebody out there goes and tells them, they're just paying graduate students to go to school, we're in deep trouble.
That's why when we hire a graduate student, he produces something.
And he works the hours he's supposed to work.
on what we feel will benefit the state, not to get him an education.
But that just also happens to be, in most cases, a byproduct of the whole process.
Not only does he get a realistic job to work on, something that he'll really learn something from, but it makes him responsible.
I don't believe in giving a kid some money to go to school.
First of all, you dream up a project for him.
It's unrealistic.
You can't kid these kids.
Pardon the pun.
They know when they're producing something worthwhile.
And they want to.
And that is why the way we do it is both an advantage to the state and to the kids' education.
What about the role of teasing, disseminating information?
It is absolutely worthless to do research, write it up, and put it on the shelf.
You've got to get it used and out on the street.
And I tell you who's a little bit better than Tease at doing that.
That's TTI.
What they do gets put on the highway and saves lives.
And we've learned a lot from them on how to get it out and get it used.
One outlet is this Invent program, which is to take the results of research and actually start businesses.
And we have no apologies for doing that whatsoever.
What about the publications and the change in publications?
I know this has been the major improvement in T's under Porter.

a major there have been many but he has done a gorgeous job and so has penny he's backed her and she's done it yeah and really getting worthwhile stuff up to then i paid for a crummy deal that frankly wasn't any good and i think penny is just getting started
I think give her two more years, I'll give her three.
Key's publications will be equivalent to Harvard and MIT, but in a different vein, in fact, a much more useful vein than theirs.
But we will be the technical publication for the state of Texas.
Now, you're talking about the thing you paid for?
You're talking about the technical bulletin?
I'm talking about whatever penny puts together.
No, I mean... My windows may become... Yeah.
Or it may be something else.
I'm talking...
I meant historically, that the thing you said you weren't proud of... Oh, we did a... Did you ever know Horn?
I'm interviewing him tomorrow afternoon.
Horn?
Well, Horn ran publications for Tees for years, and...
Until about the time you came.
Yeah.
And it was so bad that I just shut it down.
It wasn't worth the money.
And then we got a little bit ashamed of that and put out a quarterly, very technical, unsexy book.
It was technically sound.
But I doubt anybody ever looked at it.
I have.
The other flame cover, just weird.
But you started that in 72.
You started that back up again.
That was because you felt you were shamed into it?
Well, we weren't publishing anything.
Yeah, I'm shamed into it.
What does that do for the visibility of the organization?
or would help some with a limited clientele.
What would happen, I'm sure, is someone who was extremely interested technically in one of the three or four articles would probably get some good out of it.
But that's a pretty limited audience.
Because you can't, it can't be broad enough.
And we didn't have anybody knew how to do it.
This is the truth.
I didn't.
Is there a particular time period in Tees that you feel was the low point?
In Tees?
No.
When I got here in Tees, I had about less than a half million dollar budget.
And the administration consisted of Mr. Blevins, who worked for a bank in town,
And the kids go blind, and that's all.
And it has been a rather reasonable, steady growth.
I don't think you'll find any dips anywhere in it.
I don't believe there was ever a fallback year.
It's been going along on the average about 15, 20% a year.
I don't recall any low spots.
The changes from the 60s to the 70s, Dean Benson is characterizing as the 60s as a building parade of resources and the 70s a utilization of those.
Is that the same way you would characterize them?
The 60s, see I got here in 63 and I had a fairly limited role until I was made associate director.
I guess I would say there just wasn't a critical mass until about 70.
By that I mean you had enough going to be flexible enough to ride out any problems.
And that's the key to teeth.
It's very flexible.
And we shut things down if they don't work.
Such as?
Such as the remote sensing center.
We shut it down two weeks ago.
Not because it was, it was extremely good for
But right now, things are changing, and the people involved would rather be involved in electrical engineering.
But that flexibility is key to it, and our people are flexible.
Well, you've seen how environmental goes up and then it went down.
The people involved didn't change, and they went over to this strategic petroleum reserve, and that's going to go away.
But those people will be, they'll look ahead, they'll start in hazardous waste studies, you watch me, and they won't run out of money, and they won't run out of a job, but they'll shift.
They can't change their talents, but they can change what they're applying to.
And this happens all the time.
I know the interdisciplinary programs have expanded rapidly in the last few years.
Yeah.
That, of course, is the part that takes the most putting together.
But it also is the part that can take on bigger jobs.
You may look at ME, industrial, EE, and not realize that when you see ME, there's very few programs in ME that are just ME.
ME may be taking the lead role, but there'll be EEs involved, like in the robotics program, industrial engineers involved.
And then you go over to the EE program and you see microelectronics.
Will there be chemical engineers involved?
EE just happens to be taking the lead role.
So in my mind, those programs labeled MEE are just as interdisciplinary as the others.
And they have to be.
Have they been that way ever since you've been here?
That has been my greatest contribution.
I knew it had to happen.
See, I ran research at Aberdeen Proving Grounds in White Sands.
And there's nothing worthwhile you can do with one discipline, in my opinion.
There's no such thing as ME research or EE research.
It's impossible.
So that sense of cooperation is what you've tried to work with?
That is why engineering at A&M is different from most places.
Now, MFT can do the same thing, probably a little better.
But there's not many schools that can.
Was there interdisciplinary cooperation before you became associate director?
Some.
The problem just wasn't that big.
It's got to reach the critical mass before you can do that.
And that's what's fun.
When do you think it reached the critical mass?
Oh, I'd say, yeah, that's probably 74 or 75.
And that being having the talent and the equipment?
And what really, when people start coming to you, then you know you're there.
Now this hasn't happened in all areas, but it's happened in many areas.
We really don't have to look for research in turbomachinery anymore.
What we do in remote sensing, we didn't have to look for it.
And then that sort of tailed off.
So you have to shift with it.
There were, oh, eight years ago, we didn't have to look for any remote sensing research.
But that has changed.
So we're changing.
What about the data processing center?
I know it was divorced from an organization.
It never should have been under TEAS in the first place.
The only reason it was is TEAS was the only place that could underwrite it.
It just so happened that there wasn't a lot of underwriting needed.
But when you get up to a $2 million and $3 million budget,
Somebody's gotta be able to, in case there's a million dollar loss one year, cover it, because the people gotta get paid.
So the only reason it was ever in Teves was the ability to underwrite it.
And also, as I was near when they started, it could have been considered, at that time, more research than service.
But then it got to be strictly service.
It should definitely have left Tees many years ago.
But they couldn't get the act together and find a way to underwrite it.
They finally did.
And we were very happy to say sign art to you fellows.
Oh, it was a great bunch of people and they did a gorgeous job.
But it really wasn't our job to provide computing to the whole university.
It was a
I wrote his research.
Are there any other?
And there was a pain in the neck.
Are there any other divisions that have been pains in the neck that you'd like to?
Nuclear Science Center.
That's what I was going to ask you about.
That's been changed somewhat a little in the last few years too, hasn't it?
Not really.
It's been losing about a quarter of a million dollars a year, as long as I can remember.
But it's now going through the...
Yes, right.
It did report directly to me and not report to the department.
Is that at their instigation or at T's instigation?
Our instigation.
What will that do, hopefully?
Well, it hadn't worked the other way.

just a new experiment the real hope was see there had been no nuclear research in engineering up until well when Dr. Erdman came the hope was that he would increase the nuclear engineering research program to the point that it would justify the reactor most of the research at the reactor has been done at
The use of it has been by the science college and agriculture and vet medicine, not engineering.
So what we've been doing is underwriting their research program about a quarter of a million dollars a year, which is OK.
But we just seem not.
So we're stirring around and trying to find a better arrangement.
And whether we will or not, I don't know the answer, really.
We don't have enough data at this point.
I don't even really know how much these other colleges are interested in it.
They obviously aren't interested enough to pay for it.
I mean, if you're not going to make them pay for it, why are they going to volunteer?
If it's to the benefit of the whole, we can live with that.
But is it?
I don't know.
I'm trying to find out, and I'll bet I'll take it.
That's the present project, right?
I know that, I'm trying to remember the name of the fluid measurement division or something.
Well, now that goes on in aerospace.
No, it's the, I can't remember, Hall, Kenneth Hall's?
Oh, thermodynamic research.
Thermodynamics, okay, yeah.
I talked to him last week, and he was telling me about the fact that TEAS had essentially bought them from the Research Foundation.
Are there other organizations that you've done that with?
Well, we sure bailed them out.
And it worked.
And it absolutely worked.
No, I don't guess so.
That was about as bad a deal as I ever got.
It turned around pretty fast, though.
Yeah, it turned around real fast.
And I blame that all on Dick Hall.
Dick Hall's a good man.
That was just a risk you took?
It's not one you generally have taken before?
No, it isn't normal.
The fan testing research has been around forever and ever and ever.
Yeah, see that's another thing we're changing.
Okay, how are you changing that?
Well, for years it's been strictly, it does most of the testing of air moving machines in this country.
And it is accepted by all of the industry as something they believe.
If we put out the data, they believe it.
In other words, if we say this fan will move this much air per minute, then they believe us.
They don't have to check it or anything.
And we want to continue that.
But that's not research.
So what I've done is turn that whole program over to the ME department, because we have a very fine opportunity now to really do research in HVAC, which is heating, ventilating, and air conditioning.
And there is an organization that wants to join with us and build a program like we have in turbo machinery.
And this was done.
by ME people and industrial and led by ME.
So the attempt to utilize that facility, because there's a lot of stuff out there, better rather than just testing things.
We have turned it over to ME and say, OK, it's yours.
Get on with some research, and here's some resources to get you going.
So we're just trying to broaden it from a testing program to a testing and research program.
But still part of TEAS?
Yes.
Through the ME department?
Yeah.
In the interdisciplinary aspects, Invent is one of the big- Hot deal.
Yeah, the hot deal of the time.
And from other interviews I've had, part of the problem that they're
coming across with Invent is that it's not a win-win situation in terms of the need for publications from the faculty standpoint.
Is that something that you're finding with Invent, or is that the problem with other teachers?
It's peculiar.
This need for publications is

wrong i mean there is a need the need is to get promoted right and in my opinion when you publish something it is immediately worthless you can't sell it you're giving it away right if i patent it it's a different matter so i'm not that hung up on publication but at the moment at least
And it seems to have gotten worse in the last three or four years.
This hang-up on publication is copying Harvard and Yale.
They do it and that for 40 years.
It gets 400 years.
So we're copying them, or trying to, rather than do our own thing.
I think it'll ease off.
That heat will go away and become reasonable again, as it was under Benson.
There was never that fear in the faculty.
I know many who did real well and never published anything, but produced a lot.
I think that'll go away.
It's a trend at the moment.
It won't last.
Not here.
It is a problem.
It surfaces and is more visible in the event.
But it's a problem in many ways.
But anytime you set something in concrete and start counting something, you know, did you do one this move?
You're crazy.
Everything won't work.
And that'll go away.
That's just people.
Do you think it'll...
It'll get reasonable again.
Certainly we want to publish, but we don't want to...
run everybody's life on how many, whether they published two this month or only one.
That's dumb.
But it's a fear in the faculty that if they involve their self within VET at the moment is negative.
I tell you how I can fix that real quick.
Pay them a little bit more money.
Then the fear will go away.
You're not going to let it stop inventing.
No, no way.
It will not stop inventing.
I guarantee you that.
The Research Foundation, you I was a member of that austere group at one time.
It was a very fine organization.
It had a few problems.
It only had one, really.
It cost too much.
Is it living up to its expenses?
Is it paying for itself?
Their cost of doing what they do, percentage-wise, see, what they do is take a certain percent of the indirect cost.
Are you saying they could cut costs?
Yes, and do the same thing.
And also, in the case of the foundation and fees, there's a duplication there that needs to be studied.
and either the duplication removed from TEAS or from the foundation.
There's not nearly that much duplication in what they do for the university in that the university doesn't have much of a research accounting or management or anything like that.
So what the, my feeling is the foundation is geared to serve the university and it's over geared to serve TEAS.
Another solution would be for us to cut back on our county, and we're willing to do that.
If a study says that's what you ought to do, nobody's ever looked at it.
And one of these days, the federal government's going to look at it and say, you're indirect costs are too high because you're duplicating.
And you people fix it, or we're going to.
So we better fix it.
And we're thinking about doing it.
It took me a lot of reading to understand the relationship.
But the foundation's valuable.
For example, they do all the negotiating with the federal agencies for us.
And they know how to do it.
And there's always quirks with the different federal agencies that they understand.
If we didn't have them, we'd have to step up to do that.
So they're valuable to us.
I don't think they're quite as valuable as they cost.
That's the problem.
And it's not.
Anything can't be fixed.
Do they deal only with federal guys?
Mainly.
Federal and industry.
They do no dealings with the state.
And see, we do a lot of research for the state.
So we have to have a staff to do that.
They're primarily with the federal government.
Have you noticed a change in funding in terms of percentage, federal, industry?
Not in our case.
Not really.
Perhaps industry has increased modestly, and federal percentage has gone down slightly.
I like the way we have it.
We probably have the highest percentage of industry support of any engineering complex in the country.
Quite a bit.
Probably twice as much.
Which is real nice.
I'll take a job with industry any day before I will the federal government.
And then if you want to look at the federal government, there's good ones and bad ones.
The best one is DOD.
They know what they're doing.
They do their homework.
And if you do a good job, they know it.
And there's less chupac type stuff.
I guess the worst one up to date is NSF.
They don't know what they're doing.
But I believe they may be learning.
That's not really true.
I hope.
They finally decided engineering's important.
The changes in TEAS, we're also trying to look at how their change compared to the other engineering experience stations in the nation.
And I know from my research that there was, until the mid-50s, a journal of the Engineering Division of Land Grant
the association land grants.
Is there anything?
